Note:
VHDL (HDL) Translation Round-Trip Probe

End-to-end proof that the VHDL translation pipeline is REAL, not a skeleton:

    VHDL source
      -> vhdl_lexer    (tokenize: entity/architecture/signal/process,
                        port/in/out, std_logic/std_logic_vector, downto,
                        if/then/end if, <=, rising_edge, identifiers, numbers)
      -> vhdl_parser   (build design-file AST of entity/architecture nodes,
                        port-decl/signal-decl/concurrent-assign/process AST)
      -> vhdl_to_hir   (lower the design file to a HIR_PROGRAM whose "modules"
                        list carries one HIR_MODULE per design unit; an entity
                        module's body holds is_port HIR_VARIABLE_DECL nodes, an
                        architecture module's body holds the signal var-decl, a
                        concurrent HIR_ASSIGNMENT, and a process HIR_FUNCTION)
      -> hir_to_vhdl   (emit the HIR program back to VHDL source text)

The probe feeds a representative single-entity design containing:
  - an entity header with a port clause
        (clk : in std_logic; q : out std_logic_vector(7 downto 0))
  - an architecture with:
      * a signal declaration                 (signal q_reg : std_logic_vector(7 downto 0);)
      * a concurrent signal assignment        (q <= q_reg;)
      * a clocked process with an edge test and a sequential assignment
            (process(clk) begin if rising_edge(clk) then q_reg <= q_reg; end if; end process;)

It then:

  1. Drives the source through lexer -> parser -> to_hir and asserts the HIR
     root is a HIR_PROGRAM carrying a non-empty "modules" list. It locates the
     entity module (the module whose body holds an is_port variable
     declaration) and the architecture module (the module whose body holds an
     executable assignment/process), and asserts the entity's first port name
     and direction, the architecture's signal declaration name, the concurrent
     assignment's target+value identifiers, and the process function's
     sensitivity list and if-statement body all survived the first lowering.
  2. Emits the HIR back to VHDL text and asserts the text is non-empty.
  3. Re-lexes / re-parses / re-lowers the emitted VHDL text into a SECOND HIR
     program and asserts STRUCTURAL survival DIRECTLY on that second HIR: the
     program still carries modules, an entity module still exposes a port with
     the same name and direction, an architecture module still carries a signal
     declaration, a concurrent assignment with the same target+value, and a
     process function with a sensitivity list and an if body. This second-
     emission assertion is whitespace- and indentation-insensitive and so
     proves round-trip fidelity, not mere non-emptiness.

Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed). No exit_with_code.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/vhdl/vhdl_lexer.runa" as VhdlLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/vhdl/vhdl_parser.runa" as VhdlParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/vhdl/vhdl_to_hir.runa" as VhdlFrontend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/vhdl/vhdl_hir.runa" as HirNodes
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/vhdl/hir_to_vhdl.runa" as VhdlBackend
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pipeline driver: VHDL source -> HIR program node
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The VHDL pipeline exposes its stages individually: create_lexer builds the
byte-positioned lexer; next_token pulls one token at a time until TOKEN_EOF, so
the probe accumulates the full token list (EOF included) the parser expects;
create_parser/parse build the design-file AST; and VhdlFrontend.translate lowers
the whole file to a HIR_PROGRAM. Returning that program pointer (or 0 on any
stage failure) lets the caller assert on one value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "vhdl_source_to_hir" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from VhdlLexer with source
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Build the token list by pulling tokens until EOF (inclusive).
    Let tokens be proc list_create from List
    Let token_count be 0
    Let scanning be 1
    While scanning is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc next_token from VhdlLexer with lexer
        If token is equal to 0:
            Set scanning to 0
        Otherwise:
            proc list_append from List with tokens, token
            Set token_count to token_count plus 1
            Let kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
            If kind is equal to VhdlLexer.TOKEN_EOF:
                Set scanning to 0
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let parser be proc create_parser from VhdlParser with tokens, token_count
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast be proc parse from VhdlParser with tokens, token_count
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir_program be proc translate from VhdlFrontend with ast
    Return hir_program
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR program / module accessors (read the dict-tagged HIR shared model)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Every HIR node stores its kind constant under the "type" attribute. Returns it so
assertions and locators can dispatch on program / module / variable / assignment
/ function node kinds.
@End Reasoning
Process called "node_kind" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get_attribute from HirNodes with node, "type"
End Process

@Reasoning:
The HIR program root carries its lowered design units under "modules".
@End Reasoning
Process called "program_modules" takes program as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get_attribute from HirNodes with program, "modules"
End Process

@Reasoning:
A module's body is the list of its lowered items (port/signal var-decls,
assignments, process functions).
@End Reasoning
Process called "module_body" takes module as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get_attribute from HirNodes with module, "body"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Locates the entity module: the first module whose body holds an is_port
variable declaration. The entity interface lowers to a module whose ports are
HIR_VARIABLE_DECL nodes marked is_port, so this distinguishes it from the
architecture module (whose body holds executable items).
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_entity_module" takes program as Integer returns Integer:
    Let modules be proc program_modules with program
    If modules is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let module_count be proc size from List with modules
    Let m be 0
    While m is less than module_count:
        Let module be proc get from List with modules, m
        Let body be proc module_body with module
        If body is not equal to 0:
            Let item_count be proc size from List with body
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than item_count:
                Let item be proc get from List with body, i
                Let is_port be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with item, "is_port"
                If is_port is equal to 1:
                    Return module
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set m to m plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the first is_port variable declaration in a module's body, or 0 if
none. Used to assert a port's name and direction survived.
@End Reasoning
Process called "first_port" takes module as Integer returns Integer:
    Let body be proc module_body with module
    If body is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let item_count be proc size from List with body
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than item_count:
        Let item be proc get from List with body, i
        Let is_port be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with item, "is_port"
        If is_port is equal to 1:
            Return item
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Locates the architecture module: the first module whose body holds an
executable item (a HIR_ASSIGNMENT or a process HIR_FUNCTION). The architecture's
concurrent statements and process lower into the architecture module's body.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_architecture_module" takes program as Integer returns Integer:
    Let modules be proc program_modules with program
    If modules is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let module_count be proc size from List with modules
    Let m be 0
    While m is less than module_count:
        Let module be proc get from List with modules, m
        Let body be proc module_body with module
        If body is not equal to 0:
            Let item_count be proc size from List with body
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than item_count:
                Let item be proc get from List with body, i
                Let kind be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with item, "type"
                If kind is equal to HirNodes.HIR_ASSIGNMENT:
                    Return module
                End If
                If kind is equal to HirNodes.HIR_FUNCTION:
                    Return module
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set m to m plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the first body item of the requested kind within a module, or 0 if
none. Used to locate the signal declaration, the concurrent assignment, and the
process function without depending on their exact body positions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "first_item_of_kind" takes module as Integer, kind as Integer returns Integer:
    Let body be proc module_body with module
    If body is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let item_count be proc size from List with body
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than item_count:
        Let item be proc get from List with body, i
        Let item_kind be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with item, "type"
        If item_kind is equal to kind:
            Return item
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the first signal variable declaration (HIR_VARIABLE_DECL marked
is_signal) in a module body, or 0 if none. Signals lower to is_signal-tagged
variable declarations, distinct from is_port port declarations.
@End Reasoning
Process called "first_signal" takes module as Integer returns Integer:
    Let body be proc module_body with module
    If body is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let item_count be proc size from List with body
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than item_count:
        Let item be proc get from List with body, i
        Let is_signal be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with item, "is_signal"
        If is_signal is equal to 1:
            Return item
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
An assignment node stores its target and value HIR nodes under "target" and
"value"; the target is an identifier whose "name" is the assigned signal.
@End Reasoning
Process called "assignment_target_name" takes assign as Integer returns Integer:
    If assign is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let target be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with assign, "target"
    If target is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get_attribute from HirNodes with target, "name"
End Process

Process called "assignment_value_node" takes assign as Integer returns Integer:
    If assign is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get_attribute from HirNodes with assign, "value"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Structural assertions over one HIR program
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Factors the full battery of structural checks so it can run identically against
the stage-1 HIR and the round-trip (second-emission) HIR. label distinguishes
the two runs in the assertion names. Returns nothing; records into results.
@End Reasoning
Process called "assert_structure" takes results as Integer, label as Integer, program as Integer returns Integer:
    Let root_kind be proc node_kind with program
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, label, root_kind, HirNodes.HIR_PROGRAM

    Let modules be proc program_modules with program
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, label, modules
    Let module_count be proc size from List with modules
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, label, module_count, 0

    Note: Entity module: a port survives with name and direction.
    Let entity_module be proc find_entity_module with program
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, label, entity_module
    Let port be proc first_port with entity_module
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, label, port
    Let port_name be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with port, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, label, port_name, "clk"
    Let port_mode be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with port, "mode"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, label, port_mode, "in"

    Note: Architecture module: signal decl + concurrent assignment + process.
    Let arch_module be proc find_architecture_module with program
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, label, arch_module

    Let signal be proc first_signal with arch_module
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, label, signal
    Let signal_name be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with signal, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, label, signal_name, "q_reg"

    Let assign be proc first_item_of_kind with arch_module, HirNodes.HIR_ASSIGNMENT
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, label, assign
    Let assign_target be proc assignment_target_name with assign
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, label, assign_target, "q"
    Let assign_value be proc assignment_value_node with assign
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, label, assign_value
    Let assign_value_name be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with assign_value, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, label, assign_value_name, "q_reg"

    Let process_func be proc first_item_of_kind with arch_module, HirNodes.HIR_FUNCTION
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, label, process_func
    Let is_process be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with process_func, "is_process"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, label, is_process, 1
    Let sensitivity be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with process_func, "sensitivity_list"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, label, sensitivity

    Let process_body be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with process_func, "body"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, label, process_body
    Let body_count be proc size from List with process_body
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, label, body_count, 0

    Note: The process body's clocked branch lowers to a HIR_IF.
    Let if_node be 0
    Let bi be 0
    While bi is less than body_count:
        Let stmt be proc get from List with process_body, bi
        Let skind be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with stmt, "type"
        If skind is equal to HirNodes.HIR_IF:
            Set if_node to stmt
        End If
        Set bi to bi plus 1
    End While
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, label, if_node
    Let if_condition be proc get_attribute from HirNodes with if_node, "condition"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, label, if_condition

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Test entry point
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Owns the whole round trip: lower the source, assert structure on the stage-1
HIR, emit VHDL text, re-lower the emitted text, then assert the identical
structure battery on the second HIR. Returns the failed-assertion count as the
process exit code (0 == all passed).
@End Reasoning
Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "VHDL translation round-trip"

    Let source be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "entity counter is port (clk : in std_logic; q : out std_logic_vector(7 downto 0)); end entity counter; architecture rtl of counter is signal q_reg : std_logic_vector(7 downto 0); begin q <= q_reg; process(clk) begin if rising_edge(clk) then q_reg <= q_reg; end if; end process; end architecture rtl;"

    Note: --- Stage 1: source -> HIR program ---
    Let hir1 be proc vhdl_source_to_hir with source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "pipeline produced HIR program", hir1
    proc assert_structure with results, "stage-1 HIR structure survives", hir1

    Note: --- Stage 2: HIR -> VHDL text ---
    Let emitted be proc hir_to_vhdl from VhdlBackend with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend produced VHDL text", emitted
    Let emitted_len be proc string_length from StringCore with emitted
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "emitted VHDL is non-empty", emitted_len, 0

    Note: --- Stage 3: re-lower the emitted VHDL text -> HIR (the SECOND
    Note: emission), then assert the identical structural battery on it. This is
    Note: the load-bearing round-trip assertion. ---
    Let hir2 be proc vhdl_source_to_hir with emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parse of emitted VHDL produced HIR", hir2
    proc assert_structure with results, "round-trip HIR structure survives", hir2

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process
